## The Crushed Ice Trap

The Crushed Ice Trap is the most consequential buying error at 2.5ct: choosing the cushion modified brilliant (crushed ice pattern) based on how the sub-type looks in social media photos and online videos, without verifying how it reads at 8.5mm face-up in person.

**Why the trap exists.** The cushion modified brilliant dominates Blue Nile's inventory — at any carat weight, modified brilliants outnumber cushion brilliants by a wide margin. Social media images of cushion rings are predominantly modified brilliants. Buyers form their visual preference based on the sub-type they see most often, and most buyers see modified brilliants.

**What happens at 2.5ct.** Below 2ct, the modified brilliant's pattern reads as high-energy uniform sparkle — the crushed ice texture covers the stone's face in continuous fine reflections. At 8.5mm face-up, the larger face area means each individual micro-reflection also reads larger. Under certain lighting — particularly diffuse natural daylight or overcast conditions — the enlarged micro-reflection pattern can shift from "lively" to "glassy" or "wet." Some buyers describe it as the stone looking like it is filled with water rather than fire.

**The cushion brilliant at 2.5ct.** The cushion brilliant's larger, distinct facet pattern benefits from increased size. At 8.5mm, the bigger face-up area shows clearly defined flash zones, visible fire (rainbow colour dispersion at facet edges), and strong contrast between lit and dark facets. Many buyers who enter a jewellery store requesting a modified brilliant change their preference when they see a cushion brilliant at 2.5ct beside it — the contrast and fire are visually arresting at this size in a way that does not happen at 1.5ct or 2ct.

**How to avoid The Crushed Ice Trap.** Before purchasing at 2.5ct, watch Blue Nile's 360° HD video for both sub-types at this carat weight. For the modified brilliant, look specifically for contrast — do the dark facet areas create a sense of depth, or does the stone look uniformly pale and reflective with no clear flash pattern? For the cushion brilliant, watch for fire — does the stone show rainbow colour at the facet edges under the video lighting? The sub-type decision at 2.5ct is not reversible without returning the stone; treat it as carefully as the colour or clarity choice.

**Identifying which sub-type you are buying.** The GIA or IGI grading report's "Shape and Cutting Style" field states either "Cushion Modified Brilliant" or "Cushion Brilliant." On Blue Nile, the stone listing title includes the sub-type name. For the full technical breakdown of both sub-types at every carat weight, see the [lab grown cushion cut diamond guide](/lab-grown-cushion-cut-diamond).

---

## The Pillow Premium at 2.5ct

The Pillow Premium is the price difference between a cushion cut and a princess cut of identical quality — a premium cushion buyers pay over the square-cornered alternative. At 2.5ct, The Pillow Premium is no longer a minor budget consideration: it is a significant dollar amount that changes what settings and metals are accessible.

**The Pillow Premium's progression.** At the [1 carat cushion cut diamond ring](/1-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) tier, The Pillow Premium adds $200–$300 — real but manageable. At the [1.5 carat cushion cut diamond ring](/1-5-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) tier, it scales to $300–$500 in absolute dollars. At the [2 carat cushion cut diamond ring](/2-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) tier, it reaches $1,000–$2,000. At 2.5ct, the premium for GIA Ideal quality cushion over princess is approximately $2,500–$4,000 — the largest absolute dollar figure in the 1ct–3ct range.

[![2.5 carat cushion cut diamond ring rose gold pavé solitaire](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/502250/502250_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box3_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Why The Pillow Premium peaks here.** Above 2.5ct, cushion cut natural diamond supply becomes genuinely thin — fewer than 2% of mined diamonds reach 2.5ct in gem quality — and pricing per carat begins reflecting scarcity rather than purely demand-driven shape premium. The shape premium, specifically, is largest at 2.5ct because demand for cushion cuts at this size is concentrated: buyers who specifically want a large cushion know exactly what they want, and the market reflects that demand.

**Is it worth it?** If the cushion's soft, rounded outline and distinctive pillow silhouette are the reason you are buying this shape — yes. The Pillow Premium at 2.5ct is genuinely large in dollar terms, but the cushion and princess look substantially different at 8.5mm face-up. A buyer who chose cushion consciously for its visual character is paying for a real, visible distinction. A buyer who defaulted to cushion because it seemed "similar to princess but more popular" may find the premium surprising.

**The Pillow Premium in the lab market.** Lab production of cushion modified brilliants at 2.5ct is efficient, and the demand premium that pushes natural cushion pricing does not translate to lab pricing. A lab 2.5ct cushion and lab 2.5ct princess at equivalent quality grades will differ by less than $200 in most cases. For lab buyers, The Pillow Premium is effectively eliminated — choosing cushion over princess carries no material price penalty.

