## 2.5ct Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamond

The lab market at 2.5ct is where the economics of choosing lab over natural become most dramatic in the entire cushion cluster. A natural 2.5ct GIA G-VS1 Ideal costs $19,375. A lab grown 2.5ct cushion modified brilliant of equivalent or superior grades sits in the $3,500–$5,000 range — a saving of $14,000–$16,000 for a stone that is chemically, optically, and physically identical to its natural counterpart.

**Lab pricing at 2.5ct: the adjacent tier context.** Blue Nile's dataset shows the lab cushion market at 2ct (IGI D-VVS1 Ideal at [$2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) and at 3ct (GIA D-VVS1 Ideal at [$5,962](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)). Lab 2.5ct cushion modified brilliants sit in the interpolated range — approximately $3,500–$5,000 for D-VVS1 Ideal quality, depending on certification body (GIA commands a higher premium than IGI for lab stones). Browse the current [Blue Nile 2.5ct lab cushion inventory](https://www.bluenile.com/diamonds/cushion-cut-diamonds?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for live pricing.

**Why lab at 2.5ct is the strongest value case in the cushion cluster.** The savings grow with carat weight: at 1.5ct, lab saves approximately $5,000 over natural. At 2ct, the saving reaches $11,000. At 2.5ct, the saving is $14,000–$16,000. At 3ct and above, the gap exceeds $25,000. The $14,000–$16,000 saving at 2.5ct is large enough to fund an exceptional setting, the wedding, or a meaningful investment — not a minor budget difference.

**Lab colour and clarity at 2.5ct.** D colour and VVS1 clarity are standard at this price tier in the lab market, because lab production costs do not scale with quality grades the way natural mining does. A D-VVS1 lab cushion at 2.5ct for $4,000–$5,000 would cost $30,000+ in natural diamonds. The lab buyer at 2.5ct is not compromising on grades — they are acquiring strictly superior grades on paper for a fraction of the natural price.

**The Crushed Ice Trap in lab.** The sub-type decision — modified brilliant versus cushion brilliant — applies equally to lab stones. A lab 2.5ct cushion modified brilliant carries exactly the same visual character as its natural counterpart at 8.5mm face-up. The GIA or IGI certificate's "Shape and Cutting Style" field identifies the sub-type regardless of origin.

> "At 2.5ct, I always ask natural buyers: do you genuinely value natural origin — have you thought about why it matters to you — or is natural your default assumption? At 2ct, this is a $11,000 question. At 2.5ct, it is a $14,000–$16,000 question.
>
> A lab 2.5ct D-VVS1 Ideal cushion modified brilliant and a natural 2.5ct G-VS1 Ideal cushion modified brilliant sit at the same 8.5mm face-up. In a finished ring, on a hand, in all normal lighting conditions, no observer can tell which is which. The only distinction is the grading certificate — and the $14,000+ in the buyer's account." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

